<methodology slug="conflict-resolution">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>Conflict resolution using Thomas-Kilmann five modes to select strategy and Nonviolent Communication to structure messages that stay factual and actionable.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>conflict-resolution</tag>
      <tag>nvc</tag>
      <tag>thomas-kilmann</tag>
      <tag>communication</tag>
      <tag>team-dynamics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Conflict Resolution</title>
    <summary>Conflict resolution uses two complementary frameworks: Thomas-Kilmann's five modes (Competing, Collaborating, Compromising, Avoiding, Accommodating) to select the right strategy for a situation, and Marshall Rosenberg's Nonviolent Communication (NVC) four-step formula (Observation → Feeling → Need → Request) to structure the message. Mode selection determines the approach; NVC ensures the message stays factual and actionable rather than evaluative and inflammatory.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Unresolved conflicts fester into resentment, passive-aggression, and eventual explosion. The most common failure mode is using the wrong conflict mode — competing when collaboration is possible, or avoiding when the issue matters. NVC prevents the second most common failure: mixing evaluations ("you don't care") with observations ("you arrived 15 minutes late"), which puts the other person on the defensive and closes dialogue.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Drafting an NVC-structured message to address a recurring team behavior (late deliveries, skipped reviews, missed SLAs)</item>
        <item>Selecting a Thomas-Kilmann conflict mode for a specific situation before initiating a conversation</item>
        <item>Converting an emotionally charged draft message into an observation-based, non-evaluative version</item>
        <item>Preparing a mediation agenda for a retrospective where two parties have a documented disagreement</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Active real-time conflict requiring a live human mediator — written NVC scripts cannot replace live dialogue</item>
        <item>Legal disputes or HR formal complaints where documented communication must follow legal protocols</item>
        <item>Anonymous feedback systems where the goal is data aggregation, not dialogue</item>
        <item>Cross-cultural conflicts where directness norms differ significantly — adjust framework application accordingly</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Mode Selection Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Select the conflict mode before drafting any message. The wrong mode undermines even a perfectly worded NVC script.</statement>
        <rationale>Mode sets the intent (I win / we both win / no one wins). A Collaborating script delivered in a Competing posture reads as manipulative.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Competing — Use When">
      <list>
        <item>Emergency requiring immediate, decisive action</item>
        <item>Unpopular decision that is clearly correct and must be made</item>
        <item>Self-protection against someone exploiting cooperative behavior</item>
      </list>
      <note>Do not use when: Routine issues where relationship preservation matters, or when you might be wrong — competing with a flawed position destroys credibility.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Collaborating — Use When">
      <list>
        <item>The issue is important and both parties have valid interests</item>
        <item>Long-term relationship requires genuine buy-in, not compliance</item>
        <item>Time is available to explore solutions together</item>
      </list>
      <note>Do not use when: Trivial matters where the effort is disproportionate, or no trust exists between parties — collaboration requires a minimum of good faith.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Compromising — Use When">
      <list>
        <item>Issue is moderately important, parties have equal power, and time is limited</item>
        <item>Temporary settlement needed while a better solution is developed</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Avoiding — Use When">
      <list>
        <item>Trivial issue not worth the relationship cost</item>
        <item>Emotions are too high — a cooling-off period is needed before productive dialogue</item>
      </list>
      <note>Do not use when: Issue is important and will not resolve itself — avoidance becomes accumulation.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="Accommodating — Use When">
      <list>
        <item>You are factually wrong — accommodation is the honest response</item>
        <item>The issue matters more to them than to you; preserving goodwill is the priority</item>
      </list>
      <note>Do not use when: Core values or principles are at stake, or you have accommodated repeatedly in this relationship — the pattern itself becomes the problem.</note>
    </section>
    <section name="NVC Step 1: Observation vs Evaluation">
      <rule>
        <statement>State observable, verifiable facts only. Remove evaluations, judgments, and interpretations. Reference a specific instance with date or measurable frequency, not a pattern ("always", "never").</statement>
        <rationale>Evaluations trigger defensiveness. An observable fact is harder to dispute and keeps the conversation on the behavior, not the person's character.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Evaluation: "You're always late" → Observation: "You arrived at 9:15 for the 9:00 meeting on Tuesday"</item>
        <item>Evaluation: "You don't care" → Observation: "I haven't received a response to my 3 emails sent Monday-Wednesday"</item>
        <item>Evaluation: "The code is messy" → Observation: "I found 5 functions over 100 lines in the PR"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="NVC Step 2: Feeling vs Thought">
      <rule>
        <statement>Name a genuine emotion word. Reject "I feel that..." or "I feel like..." — these are thoughts, not feelings. If the word after "feel" can be replaced with "think", it is a thought.</statement>
        <rationale>"I feel that you don't respect me" is an interpretation that invites rebuttal. "I feel frustrated" names an emotion that cannot be disputed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Thought: "I feel like you don't respect me" → Feeling: "I feel frustrated"</item>
        <item>Thought: "I feel that this is unfair" → Feeling: "I feel disappointed"</item>
        <item>Positive feeling words: glad, relieved, hopeful, excited, grateful, confident</item>
        <item>Negative feeling words: frustrated, disappointed, worried, overwhelmed, hurt, confused</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="NVC Step 3: Need vs Strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Name a universal human need, not a specific strategy or demand. Needs are satisfied by many strategies; confusing need with strategy closes off solutions.</statement>
        <rationale>Universal needs (autonomy, predictability, respect, fairness) are understandable to anyone. Strategy demands ("I need you to answer faster") sound like orders and create resistance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Strategy: "I need you to answer faster" → Need: "I need responsiveness"</item>
        <item>Strategy: "I need a bigger team" → Need: "I need support"</item>
        <item>Strategy: "I need you to stop micromanaging" → Need: "I need autonomy"</item>
        <item>Universal needs: autonomy, competence, connection, safety, predictability, fairness, respect, recognition</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="NVC Step 4: Request Criteria">
      <rule>
        <statement>Make the request specific, positive (what you want, not what you don't want), and doable within the other person's power. Vague or negative requests cannot be acted on.</statement>
        <rationale>A request that cannot be executed produces agreement without behavioral change. Negative requests ("stop doing X") leave the behavior undefined.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Vague: "Be more careful" → Specific: "Would you review the checklist before submitting?"</item>
        <item>Negative: "Stop sending late-night messages" → Positive: "Would you batch non-urgent messages for the next morning?"</item>
        <item>Outside their power: "Fix the entire codebase" → Doable: "Would you pair with me for 30 min to debug this module?"</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Complete NVC Examples">
      <example type="good" title="Late delivery addressed with NVC">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[When the feature was delivered 3 days after the deadline (O),
I felt stressed (F)
because I need predictability to plan my work (N).
Would you be willing to flag delays 2 days in advance? (R)]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You never deliver on time. This is unacceptable.]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Five-Step Resolution Process">
      <rule>
        <statement>Follow the five steps in sequence: Prepare → Open → Listen → Explore → Agree. Skipping Prepare produces reactive conversations without a clear goal. Skipping Listen after sharing your view prevents understanding the other party's perspective.</statement>
        <rationale>Each step builds the foundation for the next. Opening without preparation leads to goal drift. Exploring without listening produces solutions that ignore one party's real needs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>1. PREPARE — What is the issue? What is my goal? What is their likely perspective?</item>
        <item>2. OPEN — State purpose, establish psychological safety, share your perspective (NVC)</item>
        <item>3. LISTEN — Understand their view, acknowledge feelings, ask clarifying questions</item>
        <item>4. EXPLORE — Identify shared interests, generate options together, find common ground</item>
        <item>5. AGREE — Specific actions, clear accountability (WHO does WHAT by WHEN), follow-up date</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="De-escalation When Emotions Are High">
      <rule>
        <statement>When you observe signs of escalation (raised voice, tears, silence, crossed arms), pause content and restore safety before continuing. Say what you are NOT doing to clarify intent.</statement>
        <rationale>High-emotion states shut down the prefrontal cortex and make rational problem-solving impossible. Safety must be restored before content can land.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>"Let's take 5 minutes and come back" — pause</item>
        <item>"I can see this is important to you" — acknowledge</item>
        <item>"It sounds like you're feeling frustrated" — name the emotion</item>
        <item>"I'm not saying you're wrong. I'm saying this specific outcome concerns me." — contrasting</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Avoid: "Calm down" → use: "I want to understand your perspective"</item>
        <item>Avoid: "You're wrong" → use: "I see it differently — help me understand"</item>
        <item>Avoid: "You always..." / "You never..." → use: specific instance with date</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Mediation Script for Third-Party Facilitation">
      <rule>
        <statement>As a mediator, establish ground rules at the start, give each party equal uninterrupted time, and keep exploration focused on shared interests rather than positions or blame.</statement>
        <rationale>Ground rules create a predictable, safe container. Equal speaking time prevents the dominant party from defining the narrative. Shared-interest focus opens options that position-based negotiation closes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[OPENING:
"We're here to find a solution that works for both of you.
I'm not here to judge who's right.
Ground rules: one person speaks at a time, no personal attacks, focus on future."

EXPLORATION:
[Person A]: "Share your perspective — what happened?"
[Person B]: "What did you hear? What is your view?"

FINDING COMMON GROUND:
"What do you both agree on?"
"What outcome do you both want?"

RESOLUTION:
"What would need to happen for this to be resolved?"
"What is each of you willing to do?"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Usage and Limitations">
      <p>An agent assists conflict resolution by transforming a raw, emotionally charged message draft into an NVC-structured version: it identifies evaluations disguised as observations, replaces them with factual observations, and adds a need and specific request. For mode selection, the agent receives the situation parameters (stakes, relationship importance, time available, power dynamics) and outputs a ranked recommendation with rationale. Mediation agendas are generated from a structured brief: parties, positions, shared interests, ground rules.</p>
      <p>Limitations: NVC requires the receiver to engage in good faith; an agent can draft NVC-structured messages, but the human must decide whether the relationship context supports that approach. Thomas-Kilmann mode selection depends on organizational culture, power dynamics, and relationship history that an agent cannot verify from a text prompt. De-escalation scripts written by an agent may feel scripted or patronizing if used verbatim — they are drafts for human adaptation, not final messages. Cross-cultural conflict resolution has different norms for directness, face-saving, and authority respect that general frameworks do not account for.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>NVC messages should reference a specific instance with a date or measurable fact, not a pattern ("the last 3 Monday reports" not "always")</item>
        <item>Mode selection matters more than script quality; choosing Competing when Collaborating is appropriate produces short-term compliance and long-term resentment</item>
        <item>De-escalation requires the agent-drafted script to be internalized and paraphrased by the human — verbatim reading sounds scripted and reduces trust</item>
        <item>Address conflicts when stakes are low — a small behavior addressed early via NVC is far easier than a full mediation after resentment has built up</item>
        <item>Written conflict communication (email/Slack) is only appropriate for setting up a conversation, not for the conversation itself; agent-drafted messages should always end with a request to meet</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <note>Agents may produce NVC messages that are technically correct but too formal or clinical for the relationship context — tone calibration requires human judgment.</note>
      <note>Feeling word selection is a known failure point: agents often output "I feel that you..." (a thought) instead of a genuine emotion word; validate output against the NVC feeling vocabulary.</note>
      <note>Human checkpoint required before sending any conflict-related message drafted by an agent — the agent cannot know the full relationship history, power dynamics, or organizational context.</note>
      <note>Agents asked to select a conflict mode may default to "Collaborating" in all scenarios because it sounds positive — push back and supply accurate situation parameters.</note>
      <note>Do not use agents to draft messages in active, escalated conflicts; human judgment about tone and timing is irreplaceable in high-stakes situations.</note>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/nvc-message.md" purpose="NVC message template with four labeled sections"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-nvc-rewrite.txt" purpose="Prompt for rewriting an emotionally charged message into NVC format"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-mode-selection.txt" purpose="Prompt for selecting the right Thomas-Kilmann conflict mode"/>
    </templates>
